# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: resource-quotas-k8s
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Hosted applications: From the 1990s traditional application service providers (ASPs) hosted (then-existing) applications on behalf of their customers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Depending on the limitation of the underlying application, ASPs were forced to host applications on separate machines (if multiple instances of the applications could not be executed in the same physical machine) or as separate processes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a more mature architecture which enables a similar service with lower operational cost.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Web applications: Popular consumer-oriented web applications (such as Hotmail) developed with a single application instance serving all customers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Multitenant applications represent a natural evolution from this model, offering additional customization to groups of users within (say) the same client organization.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] In a multitenancy environment, multiple customers share the same application, running on the same operating system, on the same hardware, with the same data-storage mechanism.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] The distinction between the customers is achieved during application design, so that customers do not share or see each other's data.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] This contrasts with virtualization, where components are transformed so that each customer application appears to run on a separate virtual machine.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] This is attractive because redesigning an application for multitenancy can be costly, particularly for software vendors who also continue to offer an on-premises single-tenant version of their product and would otherwise have to maintain two distinct products.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] When applications are repackaged as virtual appliances, the same appliance image can be deployed in ISV-hosted, on-premises, or trusted-third-party locations, and migrated from one deployment site to another over time.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Multitenancy allows for cost savings over and above the basic economies of scale achievable from consolidating IT resources into a single operation.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] An application instance usually incurs a certain amount of memory and processing overhead which can be substantial when multiplied by many customers, especially if the customers are small.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Multitenancy reduces this overhead by spreading it over many customers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Further cost savings may come from licensing costs of the underlying software (such as operating systems and database management systems).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Put crudely, if you can run everything on a single software instance, you only have to buy one software license.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] In addition, development of multitenant systems is more complex, and security testing is more stringent because multiple customers' data is being commingled.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Because of the additional customization complexity and the need to maintain per-tenant metadata, multitenant applications require a larger development effort.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Considerations such as how tenant data is partitioned, how per-tenant schema extensions are stored, and how shared resources are isolated must be taken into account.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Multitenancy simplifies the release management process.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] In a traditional release management process, packages containing code and database changes are distributed to client desktop and/or server machines; in the single-instance case, this would be one server machine per customer.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] These packages then have to be installed on each individual machine.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] With the multitenant model, the package typically only needs to be installed on a single server.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] This greatly simplifies the release management process, and the scale is no longer dependent on the number of customers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] At the same time, multitenancy increases the risks and impacts inherent in applying a new release version.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] As there is a single software instance serving multiple tenants, an update on this instance may cause downtime for all tenants even if the update is requested and useful for only one tenant.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Also, some bugs and issues resulted from applying the new release could manifest in other tenants' personalized view of the application.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Because of possible downtime, the moment of applying the release may be restricted depending on time usage schedule of more than one tenant.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] A central design decision in a multitenant application is how each tenant's data is isolated within shared storage.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] When tenants share compute, storage, or network resources, a single tenant generating disproportionate load can degrade performance for others, a condition known as the "noisy neighbor" problem.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Mitigations include per-tenant rate limiting, resource quotas, and isolating high-demand tenants onto dedicated resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] According to Marc Brooker, in a multi tenant architecture, unrelated and uncorrelated workloads should be grouped together.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] That's because mixing different workloads, with different needs and patterns, hide the patterns of each workload.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Grouping workloads reduces the peak-to-average ratio of the overall system; individual workloads can utilize more resources during peak times without significantly increasing the overall cost structure of the system and subsequently helps you to achieve more cost efficiency.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Note that multiple workloads from the same application, customer or industry, tend to behave as a single workload.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are typically required to provide a high degree of customization to support each target organization's needs.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/multitenancy] Multitenant applications are expected to provide adequate security, robustness and performance between multiple tenants which is provided by the layers below the application in case of multi-instance applications.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In computing, a **namespace** is a set of signs (*names*) that are used to identify and refer to objects of various kinds.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A namespace ensures that all of a given set of objects have unique names so that they can be easily identified.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Namespaces are commonly structured as hierarchies to allow reuse of names in different contexts.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] As an analogy, consider a system of naming of people where each person has a given name, as well as a family name shared with their relatives.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] If the first names of family members are unique only within each family, then each person can be uniquely identified by the combination of first name and family name; there is only one Jane Doe, though there may be many Janes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Within the namespace of the Doe family, just "Jane" suffices to unambiguously designate this person, while within the "global" namespace of all people, the full name must be used.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Prominent examples for namespaces include file systems, which assign names to files.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Some programming languages organize their variables and subroutines in namespaces.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Computer networks and distributed systems assign names to resources, such as computers, printers, websites, and remote files.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Operating systems can partition kernel resources by isolated namespaces to support OS-level virtualization containers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Similarly, hierarchical file systems organize files in directories.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Each directory is a separate namespace, so that the directories "letters" and "invoices" may both contain a file "to_jane".
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In computer programming, namespaces are typically used to group symbols and identifiers around a given task and to avoid name collisions between multiple identifiers that share the same name.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In computer networking, the Domain Name System organizes websites (and other resources) into hierarchical namespaces.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Element names are defined by the developer.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] This often results in a conflict when trying to mix XML documents from different XML applications.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] If these XML fragments were added together, there would be a name conflict.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Both contain a `<table>...</table>` element, but the elements have different content and meaning.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] An XML parser will not know how to handle these differences.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Name conflicts in XML can easily be avoided using a name prefix.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] The following XML distinguishes between information about the HTML table and furniture by prefixing "h" and "f" at the beginning of the elements.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A name in a namespace consists of a namespace name and a local name.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] The namespace name is usually applied as a prefix to the local name.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] When local names are used by themselves, name resolution is used to decide which (if any) particular name is alluded to by some particular local name.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Delegation of responsibilities between parties is important in real-world applications, such as the structure of the World Wide Web.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Namespaces allow delegation of identifier assignment to multiple name issuing organisations whilst retaining global uniqueness.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A central Registration authority registers the assigned namespace names allocated.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Each namespace name is allocated to an organisation which is subsequently responsible for the assignment of names in their allocated namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] This organisation may be a name issuing organisation that assign the names themselves, or another Registration authority which further delegates parts of their namespace to different organisations.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A naming scheme that allows subdelegation of namespaces to third parties is a **hierarchical namespace**.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A hierarchy is recursive if the syntax for the namespace names is the same for each subdelegation.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] An example of a recursive hierarchy is the Domain name system.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] An example of a non-recursive hierarchy are Uniform Resource Name representing an Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) number.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A namespace name may provide context (scope in computer science) to a name, and the terms are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] However, the context of a name may also be provided by other factors, such as the location where it occurs or the syntax of the name.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For many programming languages, namespace is a context for their identifiers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In an operating system, an example of namespace is a directory.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Each name in a directory uniquely identifies one file or subdirectory.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] As a rule, names in a namespace cannot have more than one meaning; that is, different meanings cannot share the same name in the same namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A namespace is also called a context, because the same name in different namespaces can have different meanings, each one appropriate for its namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] As well as its abstract language technical usage as described above, some languages have a specific keyword used for explicit namespace control, amongst other uses.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A namespace in computer science (sometimes also called a **name scope**) is an abstract container or environment created to hold a logical grouping of unique identifiers or symbols (i.e. names).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] An identifier defined in a namespace is associated only with that namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] The same identifier can be independently defined in multiple namespaces.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] That is, an identifier defined in one namespace may or may not have the same meaning as the same identifier defined in another namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Languages that support namespaces specify the rules that determine to which namespace an identifier (not its definition) belongs.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] This concept can be illustrated with an analogy.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Imagine that two companies, X and Y, each assign ID numbers to their employees.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] X should not have two employees with the same ID number, and likewise for Y; but it is not a problem for the same ID number to be used at both companies.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For example, if Bill works for company X and Jane works for company Y, then it is not a problem for each of them to be employee #123.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In this analogy, the ID number is the identifier, and the company serves as the namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] It does not cause problems for the same identifier to identify a different person in each namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In large computer programs or documents it is common to have hundreds or thousands of identifiers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Namespaces (or a similar technique, see Emulating namespaces) provide a mechanism for hiding local identifiers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] They provide a means of grouping logically related identifiers into corresponding namespaces, thereby making the system more modular.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Data storage devices and many modern programming languages support namespaces.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Storage devices use directories (or folders) as namespaces.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] This allows two files with the same name to be stored on the device so long as they are stored in different directories.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] C++, Python), the identifiers naming namespaces are themselves associated with an enclosing namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Thus, in these languages namespaces can nest, forming a namespace tree.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] At the root of this tree is the unnamed **global namespace**.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] It is possible to use anonymous structs as namespaces in C since C99.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In C++, a namespace is defined with a namespace block.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Within this block, identifiers can be used exactly as they are declared.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Outside of this block, the namespace specifier must be prefixed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For example, outside of `namespace abc`, `bar` must be written `abc::bar` to be accessed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] C++ includes another construct that makes this verbosity unnecessary.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] to a piece of code, the prefix `abc::` is no longer needed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Identifiers that are not explicitly declared within a namespace are considered to be in the global namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] These identifiers can be used exactly as they are declared, or, since the global namespace is unnamed, the namespace specifier `::` can be prefixed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For example, `foo` can also be written `::foo`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Namespace resolution in C++ is hierarchical.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] This means that within the hypothetical namespace `food::soup`, the identifier `Chicken` refers to `food::soup::Chicken`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] If `food::soup::Chicken` doesn't exist, it then refers to `food::Chicken`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] If neither `food::soup::Chicken` nor `food::Chicken` exist, `Chicken` refers to `::Chicken`, an identifier in the global namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Namespaces in C++ are most often used to avoid naming collisions.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Although namespaces are used extensively in recent C++ code, most older code does not use this facility because it did not exist in early versions of the language.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For example, the entire C++ Standard Library is defined within `namespace std`, but before standardization many components were originally in the global namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] The `using` statement can be used to import a symbol into the current scope.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] The use of the `using` statements in headers for reasons other than backwards compatibility (e.g., convenience) is considered to be against good code practices, as those `using` statements propagate into all translation units that include the header.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] However, modules do not export `using` statements unless explicitly marked `export`, making `using` statements safer to use.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For instance, one can import a module `wikipedia.project.util` with matching namespace `wikipedia::project::util` and then use `using` statements on symbols from that namespace to simplify verbose namespaces.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Unlike other languages like Java or Rust, C++ modules, namespaces and source file structure do not necessarily match, though it is convention to match them for clarity (for example, module `abc.def.uvw.XYZ` matches namespaced class `abc::def::uvw::XYZ` and resides in file `abc/def/uvw/XYZ.cppm`).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] `using` should be used to simplify verbose nested namespaces when modular translation units are used.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] C++11 introduces *inline namespaces*, which is such that its members are treated as if they are also members of the enclosing namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] It is declared by writing `inline namespace`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] It is akin to an implicit `using namespace` statement, meaning qualifying symbols in it is optional.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] If a namespace `a` contains an inline namespace `b`, which in turn contains another inline namespace `c`, then members of `c` can be accessed as if they were members of `a` or `b`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A primary use case for inline namespaces is ABI compatibility and versioning.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] By placing different versions of an API within distinct inline namespaces (e.g., `v1`, `v2`), and then making the currently desired version inline, library developers can manage ABI compatibility.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] When a new version is released, the inline keyword can be moved to the new version's namespace, allowing users to automatically link against the new version while still enabling access to older versions through explicit qualification.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Namespaces are heavily used in C# language.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] All .NET framework classes are organized in namespaces, to be used more clearly and to avoid chaos.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Also, custom namespaces are used extensively by programmers, to organize their work and to avoid naming collisions.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] This eliminates the need to mention the complete name of all classes in that namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In the above examples, `System` is a namespace, and `Console` and `Convert` are classes defined within `System`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Unlike C++, `using` can only import all symbols in a namespace (much like `using namespace` from C++, `use *` in Rust, or `import *` in Java).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] It cannot be used to import individual symbols and classes like it is used in Java.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Unlike C++, C# namespaces do not allow relative referencing of symbols.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For example, the class `Foo.Bar.Baz.Qux` cannot be referred to as `Baz.Qux` even if referred to from within namespace `Foo.Bar`: either the namespace `Foo.Bar.Baz` must be imported to refer to class `Qux`, or `Foo.Bar.Baz.Qux` must be fully qualified.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In Java, the idea of a namespace is embodied in Java packages.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] All code belongs to a package, although that package need not be explicitly named.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Code from other packages is accessed by prefixing the package name before the appropriate identifier, for example `class String` in `package java.lang` can be referred to as `java.lang.String` (this is known as the fully qualified class name).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Like C++, Java offers a construct that makes it unnecessary to type the package name (`import`).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] However, certain features (such as reflection) require the programmer to use the fully qualified name.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Unlike C++, namespaces in Java are not hierarchical as to the syntax of the language.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] However, packages are named in a hierarchical manner.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For example, all packages beginning with `java` are a part of the Java platform—the package `java.lang` contains classes core to the language, and `java.lang.reflect` contains core classes specifically relating to reflection.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In Java (and Ada, C#, and others), namespaces/packages express semantic categories of code.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For example, in C#, `namespace System` contains code provided by the system (the .NET framework).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] How specific these categories are and how deep the hierarchies go differ from language to language.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Function and class scopes can be viewed as implicit namespaces that are inextricably linked with visibility, accessibility, and object lifetime.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In Java, packages cannot be partially qualified like they can in C++.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For instance, it is not possible to import the `java` namespace and then refer to `java.util.ArrayList` as `util.ArrayList`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Symbols must either be fully qualified or imported completely into scope.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] `import` statements are not transitive nor can they be deliberately marked `export` like in C++.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] All `import` statements must appear at the beginning of the file, and cannot be written at any other scope.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] This is in contrast to C++, where the `std` namespace can be imported by writing `using namespace std;`, and then `std::chrono::system_clock` can be referred to as `chrono::system_clock`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Because Java does not support independent functions outside of classes, static class methods and so-called "utility classes" (classes with private constructors and all methods and fields static) are the equivalent to C++-style namespaces.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Some examples are `java.lang.Math`, which contains the constants like `Math.PI` and methods like `Math.sin()`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] `import` statements can be used to import all symbols in a package, called a glob import, which is similar to `using namespace` in C++.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For instance, writing `import java.util.*;` imports all classes in the `java.util` package.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] This however, can cause symbol pollution within a file.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Furthermore, using glob import statements on packages that have classes with the same name can cause ambiguity, and will fail to compile.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] However, `java.lang.*` is implicitly imported into all Java source files by default.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Kotlin packages are very similar to Java packages, but unlike Java where only class-like objects may reside directly in a package, any top-level symbol (such as a variable, class, type alias, etc.) may live directly inside a package.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Namespaces were introduced into PHP from version 5.3 onwards.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Naming collision of classes, functions and variables can be avoided.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In PHP, a namespace is defined with a namespace block.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In Python, namespaces are defined by the individual modules, and since modules can be contained in hierarchical packages, then namespaces are hierarchical too.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In general when a module is imported then the names defined in the module are defined via that module's namespace, and are accessed in from the calling modules by using the fully qualified name.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Since this directly imports names (without qualification) it can overwrite existing names with no warnings.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A special form of the statement is `from ... import *` which imports all names defined in the named package directly in the calling module's namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In Rust, a namespace is called a "module" and declared using `mod`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Symbols inside the module are by default private, and cannot be accessed externally, unless declared with the `pub` keyword which exposes them.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Modules can have sub-modules inside of them, allowing for nested namespaces.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Similar to the `using` keyword in C++, Rust has the `use` keyword to import symbols into the current scope.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Writing `mod util;` indicates to the compiler to find either a file named `util.rs` or `util/mod.rs`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] `crate` in a `use` statement refers to the root of the current "crate" (project), while `super` can be used to refer to the parent module.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] The `use` keyword in Rust is more versatile than its counterpart `using` in C++.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In addition to importing single symbols, symbol aliasing with `as` and glob imports, `use` can import multiple symbols on the same line using braces (which may be nested), import individual namespaces, and do all of the above in a single statement.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In XML, the XML namespace specification enables the names of elements and attributes in an XML document to be unique, similar to the role of namespaces in programming languages.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Using XML namespaces, XML documents may contain element or attribute names from more than one XML vocabulary.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In SAP systems (especially ABAP environments), namespaces are used to prevent naming collisions between standard SAP-delivered objects and customer or partner developments.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] A namespace identifier is delimited with “/” (for example `/MYNS/`) and is reserved via SAP’s namespace registration process.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Once reserved, objects created under that namespace are uniquely identifiable and protected from unintended overwrite by SAP upgrades or imports.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In modern SAP landscapes (such as ABAP in the cloud and HDI containers), namespaces are also used to semantically group development artifacts or bundles.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] In programming languages lacking language support for namespaces, namespaces can be emulated to some extent by using an identifier naming convention.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] For example, C libraries such as libpng often use a fixed prefix for all functions and variables that are part of their exposed interface.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] This naming convention provides reasonable assurance that the identifiers are unique and can therefore be used in larger programs without naming collisions.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/namespace] Likewise, many packages originally written in Fortran (e.g., BLAS, LAPACK) reserve the first few letters of a function's name to indicate the group to which the function belongs.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] By default, containers run with unbounded compute resources on a Kubernetes cluster.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] Using Kubernetes resource quotas, administrators (also termed *cluster operators*) can restrict consumption and creation of cluster resources (such as CPU time, memory, and persistent storage) within a specified namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] Within a namespace, a Pod can consume as much CPU and memory as is allowed by the ResourceQuotas that apply to that namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] As a cluster operator, or as a namespace-level administrator, you might also be concerned about making sure that a single object cannot monopolize all available resources within a namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] A LimitRange is a policy to constrain the resource allocations (limits and requests) that you can specify for each applicable object kind (such as Pod or PersistentVolumeClaim) in a namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] Kubernetes constrains resource allocations to Pods in a particular namespace whenever there is at least one LimitRange object in that namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] The name of a LimitRange object must be a valid DNS subdomain name.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] A LimitRange does **not** check the consistency of the default values it applies.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] This means that a default value for the *limit* that is set by LimitRange may be less than the *request* value specified for the container in the spec that a client submits to the API server.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] If that happens, the final Pod will not be schedulable.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] For example, you define a LimitRange with below manifest:Note:The following examples operate within the default namespace of your cluster, as the namespace parameter is undefined and the LimitRange scope is limited to the namespace level.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] This implies that any references or operations within these examples will interact with elements within the default namespace of your cluster.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] You can override the operating namespace by configuring namespace in the `metadata.namespace` field.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] In the case where the total limits of the namespace is less than the sum of the limits of the Pods/Containers, there may be contention for resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] In this case, the Containers or Pods will not be created.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] Neither contention nor changes to a LimitRange will affect already created resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/policy-limit-range] Refer to the LimitRanger design document for context and historical information.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] In computer programming, **resource management** refers to techniques for managing resources (components with limited availability).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Computer programs may manage their own resources by using features exposed by programming languages (Elder, Jackson & Liblit (2008) is a survey article contrasting different approaches), or may elect to manage them by a host – an operating system or virtual machine – or another program.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Host-based management is known as *resource tracking,* and consists of cleaning up resource leaks: terminating access to resources that have been acquired but not released after use.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This is known as *reclaiming* resources, and is analogous to garbage collection for memory.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] On many systems, the operating system reclaims resources after the process makes the exit system call.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] The omission of releasing a resource when a program has finished using it is known as a resource leak, and is an issue in sequential computing.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Multiple processes wish to access a limited resource can be an issue in concurrent computing, and is known as resource contention.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Resource management seeks to control access in order to prevent both of these situations.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Formally, resource management (preventing resource leaks) consists of ensuring that a resource is released if and only if it is successfully acquired.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This general problem can be abstracted as "*before,* *body,* and *after*" code, which normally are executed in this order, with the condition that the *after* code is called if and only if the *before* code successfully completes, regardless of whether the *body* code executes successfully or not.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This is also known as *execute around* or a *code sandwich,* and occurs in various other contexts, such as a temporary change of program state, or tracing entry and exit into a subroutine.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] However, resource management is the most commonly cited application.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] In aspect-oriented programming, such execute around logic is a form of *advice*.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] In the terminology of control flow analysis, resource release must postdominate successful resource acquisition; failure to ensure this is a bug, and a code path that violates this condition causes a resource leak.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are often minor problems, generally not crashing the program, but instead causing some slowdown to the program or the overall system.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] However, they may cause crashes – either the program itself or other programs – due to *resource exhaustion:* if the system runs out of resources, acquisition requests fail.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This can present a security bug if an attack can cause resource exhaustion.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks may happen under regular program flow – such as simply forgetting to release a resource – or only in exceptional circumstances, such as when a resource is not released if there is an exception in another part of the program.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are very frequently caused by early exit from a subroutine, either by a `return` statement, or an exception raised either by the subroutine itself, or a deeper subroutine that it calls.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] While resource release due to return statements can be handled by carefully releasing within the subroutine before the return, exceptions cannot be handled without some additional language facility that guarantees that release code is executed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] More subtly, successful resource acquisition must dominate resource release, as otherwise the code will try to release a resource it has not acquired.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] The consequences of such an incorrect release range from being silently ignored to crashing the program or unpredictable behavior.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] These bugs generally manifest rarely, as they require resource allocation to first fail, which is generally an exceptional case.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Further, the consequences may not be serious, as the program may already be crashing due to failure to acquire an essential resource.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] However, these can prevent recovery from the failure, or turn an orderly shutdown into a disorderly shutdown.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] In computer science, resource contention refers to a conflict that arises when multiple entities attempt to access a shared resource, like random access memory, disk storage, cache memory, internal buses, or external network devices.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Memory can be treated as a resource, but memory management is usually considered separately, primarily because memory allocation and deallocation is significantly more frequent than acquisition and release of other resources, such as file handles.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Memory managed by an *external* system has similarities to both (internal) memory management (since it is memory) and resource management (since it is managed by an external system).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Examples include memory managed via native code and used from Java (via Java Native Interface); and objects in the Document Object Model (DOM), used from JavaScript.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] In both these cases, the memory manager (garbage collector) of the runtime environment (virtual machine) is unable to manage the external memory (there is no shared memory management), and thus the external memory is treated as a resource, and managed analogously.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] However, cycles between systems (JavaScript referring to the DOM, referring back to JavaScript) can make management difficult or impossible.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Lexical management, when applicable, allows a better separation of concerns and is less error-prone.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This is correct if the intervening `...` code does not contain an early exit (`return`), the language does not have exceptions, and `open` is guaranteed to succeed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] However, it causes a resource leak if there is a return or exception, and causes an incorrect release of unacquired resource if `open` can fail.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] There are two more fundamental problems: the acquisition-release pair is not adjacent (the release code must be written far from the acquisition code), and resource management is not encapsulated – the programmer must manually ensure that they are always paired.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] In combination, these mean that acquisition and release must be explicitly paired, but cannot be placed together, thus making it easy for these to not be paired correctly.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This ensures correct release even if there is a return within the body or an exception thrown.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Further, note that the acquisition occurs *before* the `try` clause, ensuring that the `finally` clause is only executed if the `open` code succeeds (without throwing an exception), assuming that "no exception" means "success" (as is the case for `open` in Python).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] While this ensures correct resource management, it fails to provide adjacency or encapsulation.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] There are many variations in the implementation, and there are also significantly different approaches.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] The most common approach to resource management across languages is to use unwind protection, which is called when execution exits a scope – by execution running off the end of the block, returning from within the block, or an exception being thrown.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This works for stack-managed resources, and is implemented in many languages, including C#, Common Lisp, Java, Python, Ruby, and Scheme.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] The main problems with this approach is that the release code (most commonly in a `finally` clause) may be very distant from the acquisition code (it lacks *adjacency*), and that the acquisition and release code must always be paired by the caller (it lacks *encapsulation*).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] An alternative, more imperative approach, is to write asynchronous code in direct style: acquire a resource, and then in the next line have a *deferred* release, which is called when the scope is exited – synchronous acquisition followed by asynchronous release.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This originated in C++ as the ScopeGuard class, by Andrei Alexandrescu and Petru Marginean in 2000, with improvements by Joshua Lehrer, and has direct language support in D via the `scope` keyword (ScopeGuardStatement), where it is one approach to exception safety, in addition to RAII (see below).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] It has also been included in Go, as the `defer` statement.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This approach lacks encapsulation – one must explicitly match acquisition and release – but avoids having to create an object for each resource (code-wise, avoid writing a class for each type of resource).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] In object-oriented programming, resources are encapsulated within objects that use them, such as a `file` object having a field whose value is a file descriptor (or more general file handle).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This allows the object to use and manage the resource without users of the object needing to do so.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] However, there is a wide variety of ways that objects and resources can be related.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Firstly, there is the question of ownership: does an object *have* a resource?
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Most common is to acquire a resource during object creation, and then explicitly release it via an instance method, commonly called `dispose`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This is analogous to traditional file management (acquire during `open`, release by explicit `close`), and is known as the dispose pattern.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This is the basic approach used in several major modern object-oriented languages, including Java, C# and Python, and these languages have additional constructs to automate resource management.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] However, even in these languages, more complex object relationships result in more complex resource management, as discussed below.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] A natural approach is to make holding a resource be a class invariant: resources are acquired during object creation (specifically initialization), and released during object destruction (specifically finalization).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This is known as Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII), and ties resource management to object lifetime, ensuring that live objects have all necessary resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Other approaches do not make holding the resource a class invariant, and thus objects may not have necessary resources (because they've not been acquired yet, have already been released, or are being managed externally), resulting in errors such as trying to read from a closed file.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This approach ties resource management to memory management (specifically object management), so if there are no memory leaks (no object leaks), there are no resource leaks.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] RAII works naturally for heap-managed resources, not only stack-managed resources, and is composable: resources held by objects in arbitrarily complicated relationships (a complicated object graph) are released transparently simply by object destruction (so long as this is done properly!).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Firstly, because resources are expensive, it is desirable to release them promptly, so objects holding resources should be destroyed as soon as they become garbage (are no longer in use).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] However, most modern automatic memory management is non-deterministic, making no guarantees that objects will be destroyed promptly or even at all!
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This is because it is cheaper to leave some garbage allocated than to precisely collect each object immediately on its becoming garbage.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Secondly, releasing resources during object destruction means that an object must have a *finalizer* (in deterministic memory management known as a *destructor*) – the object cannot simply be deallocated – which significantly complicates and slows garbage collection.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] When multiple objects rely on a single resource, resource management can be complicated.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] A fundamental question is whether a "has a" relationship is one of *owning* another object (object composition), or *viewing* another object (object aggregation).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] A common case is when one two objects are chained, as in pipe and filter pattern, the delegation pattern, the decorator pattern, or the adapter pattern.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] If the second object (which is not used directly) holds a resource, is the first object (which is used directly) responsible for managing the resource?
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This is generally answered identically to whether the first object *owns* the second object: if so, then the owning object is also responsible for resource management ("having a resource" is transitive), while if not, then it is not.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Further, a single object may "have" several other objects, owning some and viewing others.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Both cases are commonly found, and conventions differ.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] In object aggregation, nothing needs to be done by the viewing object, as it is not responsible for the resource.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Java Class Library, `Reader#close()` closes the underlying stream, and these can be chained.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] For example, a `BufferedReader` may contain a `InputStreamReader`, which in turn contains a `FileInputStream`, and calling `close` on the `BufferedReader` in turn closes the `InputStreamReader`, which in turn closes the `FileInputStream`, which in turn releases the system file resource.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] By contrast, in Python, a csv.reader does not own the `file` that it is reading, so there is no need (and it is not possible) to close the reader, and instead the `file` itself must be closed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] Various mechanisms exist to allow greater control of resource management.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Google Closure Library, the `goog.Disposable` class provides a `registerDisposable` method to register other objects to be disposed with this object, together with various lower-level instance and class methods to manage disposal.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] In structured programming, stack resource management is done simply by nesting code sufficiently to handle all cases.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This requires only a single return at the end of the code, and can result in heavily nested code if many resources must be acquired, which is considered an anti-pattern by some – the *Arrow Anti Pattern,* due to the triangular shape from the successive nesting.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] One other approach, which allows early return but consolidates cleanup in one place, is to have a single exit return of a function, preceded by cleanup code, and to use goto to jump to the cleanup before exit.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-management-computing] This is infrequently seen in modern code, but occurs in some uses of C.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] When several users or teams share a cluster with a fixed number of nodes, there is a concern that one team could use more than its fair share of resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] A resource quota, defined by a ResourceQuota object, provides constraints that limit aggregate resource consumption per namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] A ResourceQuota can also limit the quantity of objects that can be created in a namespace by API kind, as well as the total amount of infrastructure resources that may be consumed by API objects found in that namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Neither contention nor changes to quota will affect already created resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You often do not create Pods directly; for example, you more usually create a workload management object such as a Deployment.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] If you create a Deployment that tries to use more resources than are available, the creation of the Deployment (or other workload management object) **succeeds**, but the Deployment may not be able to get all of the Pods it manages to exist.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] In that case you can check the status of the Deployment, for example with `kubectl describe`, to see what has happened.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You can use a LimitRange to automatically set a default request for these resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] The name of a ResourceQuota object must be a valid DNS subdomain name.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] In the case where the total capacity of the cluster is less than the sum of the quotas of the namespaces, there may be contention for resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] This is handled on a first-come-first-served basis.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] ResourceQuota support is enabled by default for many Kubernetes distributions.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] It is enabled when the API server `--enable-admission-plugins=` flag has `ResourceQuota` as one of its arguments.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] A resource quota is enforced in a particular namespace when there is a ResourceQuota in that namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] The ResourceQuota mechanism lets you enforce different kinds of limits.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] This section describes the types of limit that you can enforce.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You can limit the total sum of compute resources that can be requested in a given namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] In addition to the resources mentioned above, in release 1.10, quota support for extended resources is added.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] As overcommit is not allowed for extended resources, it makes no sense to specify both `requests` and `limits` for the same extended resource in a quota.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] So for extended resources, only quota items with prefix `requests.` are allowed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] See Viewing and Setting Quotas for more details.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] DRA (Dynamic Resource Allocation) resource claims can request DRA resources by device class.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] All devices requested from resource claims or extended resources are counted towards all three quotas listed above.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] `requests.example.com/gpu: 4`, also counts the devices provided by device plugin.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You can limit the total sum of storage for volumes that can be requested in a given namespace.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] In addition, you can limit consumption of storage resources based on associated StorageClass.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] When using a CRI container runtime, container logs will count against the ephemeral storage quota.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] This can result in the unexpected eviction of pods that have exhausted their storage quotas.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Refer to Logging Architecture for details.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] For example, the PodTemplate API is in the core API group and so if you want to limit the number of PodTemplate objects in a namespace, you use `count/podtemplates`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] These types of quotas are useful to protect against exhaustion of control plane storage.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] For example, you may want to limit the number of Secrets in a server given their large size.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Too many Secrets in a cluster can actually prevent servers and controllers from starting.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You can set a quota for Jobs to protect against a poorly configured CronJob.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] CronJobs that create too many Jobs in a namespace can lead to a denial of service.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] If you define a quota this way, it applies to Kubernetes' APIs that are part of the API server, and to any custom resources backed by a CustomResourceDefinition.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] For example, to create a quota on a `widgets` custom resource in the `example.com` API group, use `count/widgets.example.com`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] If you use API aggregation to add additional, custom APIs that are not defined as CustomResourceDefinitions, the core Kubernetes control plane does not enforce quota for the aggregated API.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] The extension API server is expected to provide quota enforcement if that's appropriate for the custom API.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] This is a list of common examples of object kinds that you may want to put under object count quota, listed by the configuration string that you would use.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] There is another syntax only to set the same type of quota, that only works for certain API kinds.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] For example, `pods` quota counts and enforces a maximum on the number of `pods` created in a single namespace that are not terminal.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You might want to set a `pods` quota on a namespace to avoid the case where a user creates many small pods and exhausts the cluster's supply of Pod IPs.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You can find more examples on Viewing and Setting Quotas.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] ResourceQuotas are independent of the cluster capacity.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] So, if you add nodes to your cluster, this does *not* automatically give each namespace the ability to consume more resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Such policies could be implemented using `ResourceQuotas` as building blocks, by writing a "controller" that watches the quota usage and adjusts the quota hard limits of each namespace according to other signals.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Note that resource quota divides up aggregate cluster resources, but it creates no restrictions around nodes: pods from several namespaces may run on the same node.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Each quota can have an associated set of `scopes`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] A quota will only measure usage for a resource if it matches the intersection of enumerated scopes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] When a scope is added to the quota, it limits the number of resources it supports to those that pertain to the scope.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Resources specified on the quota outside of the allowed set results in a validation error.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] ResourceQuotas with a scope set can also have a optional `scopeSelector` field.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You define one or more *match expressions* that specify an `operators` and, if relevant, a set of `values` to match.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] If the `operator` is `In` or `NotIn`, the `values` field must have at least one value.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] If the `operator` is `Exists` or `DoesNotExist`, the `values` field must *NOT* be specified.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] This scope only tracks quota consumed by Pods.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] It only matches pods that have the best effort QoS class.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] The `operator` for a `scopeSelector` must be `Exists`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] It only matches pods that have the Guaranteed or Burstable QoS class.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] This scope only tracks quota consumed by Pods that are not terminating.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] A Pod is not terminating if the `.spec.activeDeadlineSeconds` field is unset.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] This scope only tracks quota consumed by Pods that are terminating.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] A Pod is considered as *terminating* if the `.spec.activeDeadlineSeconds` field is set to any number.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You can use `CrossNamespacePodAffinity` quota scope to limit which namespaces are allowed to have pods with affinity terms that cross namespaces.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Specifically, it controls which pods are allowed to set `namespaces` or `namespaceSelector` fields in pod (anti)affinity terms.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Preventing users from using cross-namespace affinity terms might be desired since a pod with anti-affinity constraints can block pods from all other namespaces from getting scheduled in a failure domain.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Using this scope, you (as a cluster administrator) can prevent certain namespaces - such as `foo-ns` in the example below - from having pods that use cross-namespace pod affinity.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] With the above configuration, pods can use `namespaces` and `namespaceSelector` in pod affinity only if the namespace where they are created have a resource quota object with `CrossNamespacePodAffinity` scope and a hard limit greater than or equal to the number of pods using those fields.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] A ResourceQuota with a PriorityClass scope only matches Pods that have a particular priority class, and only if any `scopeSelector` in the quota spec selects a particular Pod.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Pods can be created at a specific priority.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You can control a pod's consumption of system resources based on a pod's priority, by using the `scopeSelector` field in the quota spec.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] This example creates a ResourceQuota matches it with pods at specific priorities.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Verify that `Used` quota is `0` using `kubectl describe quota`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Verify that "Used" stats for "high" priority quota, `pods-high`, has changed and that the other two quotas are unchanged.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] It may be desired that pods at a particular priority, such as "cluster-services", should be allowed in a namespace, if and only if, a matching quota object exists.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] With this mechanism, operators are able to restrict usage of certain high priority classes to a limited number of namespaces and not every namespace will be able to consume these priority classes by default.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] 2. the Pod's `priorityClassName` is specified to a value other than `cluster-services`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] 3. the Pod's `priorityClassName` is set to `cluster-services`, it is to be created in the `kube-system` namespace, and it has passed the resource quota check.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] A Pod creation request is rejected if its `priorityClassName` is set to `cluster-services` and it is to be created in a namespace other than `kube-system`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] This scope only tracks quota consumed by PersistentVolumeClaims.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] PersistentVolumeClaims can be created with a specific VolumeAttributesClass, and might be modified after creation.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] You can control a PVC's consumption of storage resources based on the associated VolumeAttributesClasses, by using the `scopeSelector` field in the quota spec.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] A relevant ResourceQuota is matched and consumed only if the ResourceQuota has a `scopeSelector` that selects the PVC.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/resource-quotas] Read Limit Storage Consumption to learn more about this.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:resource-quotas-k8s/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
